# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: quadtree
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:quadtree/grid-file] In computer science, a **grid file** or **bucket grid** is a point access method which splits a space into a non-periodic grid where one or more cells of the grid refer to a small set of points.
[src:quadtree/grid-file] Grid files (a symmetric data structure) provide an efficient method of storing these indexes on disk to perform complex data lookups.
[src:quadtree/grid-file] It provides a grid of *n*-dimensions where *n* represents how many keys can be used to reference a single point.
[src:quadtree/grid-file] Grid files do not contain any data themselves but instead contain references to the correct bucket.
[src:quadtree/grid-file] A grid file is usually used in cases where a single value can be referenced by multiple keys.
[src:quadtree/grid-file] A grid file began being used because "traditional file structures that provide multikey access to records, for example, inverted files, are extensions of file structures originally designed for single-key access.
[src:quadtree/grid-file] In a traditional single dimensional data structure (e.g. hash), a search on a single criterion is usually very simple but searching for a second criterion can be much more complex.
[src:quadtree/grid-file] Grid files represent a special kind of hashing, where the traditional hash is replaced by a grid directory.
[src:quadtree/grid-file] Consider a database containing data from a census.
[src:quadtree/grid-file] A single record represents a single household, and all records are grouped into buckets.
[src:quadtree/grid-file] All records in a bucket can be indexed by either their city (which is the same for all records in the bucket), and the streets in that city whose names begin with the same letter.
[src:quadtree/grid-file] A grid file can be used to provide an efficient index for this structure, where records come in groupings of 26, each of them relating to street names in a city starting with one of the letters of the alphabet.
[src:quadtree/grid-file] This structure can be thought of as an array, table, or grid with two dimensions which we will call the x and y axes.
[src:quadtree/grid-file] One may consider the x-axis to be the city and the y-axis to be each of the letters in the alphabet, or alternatively, the first letter of each street.
[src:quadtree/grid-file] Each record in this structure is known as a cell.
[src:quadtree/grid-file] Each cell will contain a pointer to the appropriate bucket in the database where the actual data is stored.
[src:quadtree/grid-file] An extra cell, or record header, may be required to store the name of the city.
[src:quadtree/grid-file] Other cells grouped with it will only need to contain the pointer to their respective bucket, since the first cell corresponds to street names beginning with "A", the second to "B", and so on.
[src:quadtree/grid-file] The database can be further extended to contain a continent field to expand the census to other continents.
[src:quadtree/grid-file] This would cause records in the same bucket to correspond to households on a street beginning with the same letter, in the same city, in the same continent.
[src:quadtree/grid-file] The cells in the grid file would then consist of a city header, and six (one for each continent, not including Antarctica) groupings of 26 cells relating to the streets with the same starting letter, in the same city, on the same continent and could now be thought of as a three-dimensional array.
[src:quadtree/hilbert-curve] The **Hilbert curve** (also known as the **Hilbert space-filling curve**) is a continuous fractal space-filling curve first described by the German mathematician David Hilbert in 1891, as a variant of the space-filling Peano curves discovered by Giuseppe Peano in 1890.
[src:quadtree/hilbert-curve] Because it is space-filling, its Hausdorff dimension is 2 (precisely, its image is the unit square, whose dimension is 2 in any definition of dimension; its graph is a compact set homeomorphic to the closed unit interval, with Hausdorff dimension 1).
[src:quadtree/hilbert-curve] The Hilbert curve is constructed as a limit of piecewise linear curves.
[src:quadtree/hilbert-curve] The length of the n th curve is $\textstyle 2^{n}-{1 \over 2^{n}}$ , i.e., the length grows exponentially with n , even though each curve is contained in a square with area 1 .
[src:quadtree/hilbert-curve] Both the true Hilbert curve and its discrete approximations are useful because they give a mapping between 1D and 2D space that preserves locality fairly well.
[src:quadtree/hilbert-curve] This means that two data points which are close to each other in one-dimensional space are also close to each other after folding.
[src:quadtree/hilbert-curve] Because of this locality property, the Hilbert curve is widely used in computer science.
[src:quadtree/hilbert-curve] For example, the range of IP addresses used by computers can be mapped into a picture using the Hilbert curve.
[src:quadtree/hilbert-curve] Code to generate the image would map from 2D to 1D to find the color of each pixel, and the Hilbert curve is sometimes used because it keeps nearby IP addresses close to each other in the picture.
[src:quadtree/hilbert-curve] The locality property of the Hilbert curve has also been used to design algorithms for exploring regions with mobile robots and indexing geospatial location data.
[src:quadtree/hilbert-curve] In an algorithm called Riemersma dithering, grayscale photographs can be converted to a dithered black-and-white image using thresholding, with the leftover amount from each pixel added to the next pixel along the Hilbert curve.
[src:quadtree/hilbert-curve] Code to do this would map from 1D to 2D, and the Hilbert curve is sometimes used because it does not create the distracting patterns that would be visible to the eye if the order were simply left to right across each row of pixels.
[src:quadtree/hilbert-curve] Hilbert curves in higher dimensions are an instance of a generalization of Gray codes, and are sometimes used for similar purposes, for similar reasons.
[src:quadtree/hilbert-curve] For multidimensional databases, Hilbert order has been proposed to be used instead of Z order because it has better locality-preserving behavior.
[src:quadtree/hilbert-curve] For example, Hilbert curves have been used to compress and accelerate R-tree indexes (see Hilbert R-tree).
[src:quadtree/hilbert-curve] They have also been used to help compress data warehouses.
[src:quadtree/hilbert-curve] The linear distance of any point along the curve can be converted to coordinates in *n* dimensions for a given *n*, and vice versa, using any of several standard mathematical techniques such as Skilling's method.
[src:quadtree/hilbert-curve] It is possible to implement Hilbert curves efficiently even when the data space does not form a square.
[src:quadtree/hilbert-curve] Moreover, there are several possible generalizations of Hilbert curves to higher dimensions.
[src:quadtree/hilbert-curve] The Hilbert Curve can be expressed by a rewrite system (L-system).
[src:quadtree/hilbert-curve] Here, "F" means "draw forward", "+" means "turn left 90°", "-" means "turn right 90°" (see turtle graphics), and "A" and "B" are ignored during drawing.
[src:quadtree/hilbert-curve] The Hilbert Curve is commonly used among rendering images or videos.
[src:quadtree/hilbert-curve] Common programs such as Blender and Cinema 4D use the Hilbert Curve to trace the objects, and render the scene.
[src:quadtree/hilbert-curve] The slicer software used to convert 3D models into toolpaths for a 3D printer typically has the Hilbert curve as an option for an infill pattern.
[src:quadtree/octree] An **octree** is a tree data structure in which each internal node has exactly eight children.
[src:quadtree/octree] Octrees are most often used to partition a three-dimensional space by recursively subdividing it into eight octants.
[src:quadtree/octree] Octrees are the three-dimensional analog of quadtrees.
[src:quadtree/octree] The word is derived from *oct* (Greek root meaning "eight") + *tree*.
[src:quadtree/octree] Octrees are often used in 3D graphics and 3D game engines.
[src:quadtree/octree] Each node in an octree subdivides the space it represents into eight octants.
[src:quadtree/octree] In a point region (PR) octree (analogous to a point quadtree), the node stores an explicit three-dimensional point, which is the "center" of the subdivision for that node; the point defines one of the corners for each of the eight children.
[src:quadtree/octree] In a matrix-based (MX) octree (analogous to a region quadtree), the subdivision point is implicitly the center of the space the node represents.
[src:quadtree/octree] The root node of a PR octree can represent infinite space; the root node of an MX octree must represent a finite bounded space so that the implicit centers are well-defined.
[src:quadtree/octree] Note that octrees are not the same as *k*-d trees: *k*-d trees split along a dimension and octrees split around a point.
[src:quadtree/octree] Also *k*-d trees are always binary, which is not the case for octrees.
[src:quadtree/octree] By using a depth-first search the nodes are to be traversed and only required surfaces are to be viewed.
[src:quadtree/octree] A spatial subdivision much like an octree was used in 1934, in the Whitney covering lemma in mathematics.
[src:quadtree/octree] The octree color quantization algorithm, invented by Gervautz and Purgathofer in 1988, encodes image color data as an octree up to nine levels deep.
[src:quadtree/octree] Octrees are used because $2^{3}=8$ and there are three color components in the RGB system.
[src:quadtree/octree] The node index to branch out from at the top level is determined by a formula that uses the most significant bits of the red, green, and blue color components, e.g.
[src:quadtree/octree] The next lower level uses the next bit significance, and so on.
[src:quadtree/octree] Less significant bits are sometimes ignored to reduce the tree size.
[src:quadtree/octree] The algorithm is highly memory efficient because the tree's size can be limited.
[src:quadtree/octree] The bottom level of the octree consists of leaf nodes that accrue color data not represented in the tree; these nodes initially contain single bits.
[src:quadtree/octree] If much more than the desired number of palette colors are entered into the octree, its size can be continually reduced by seeking out a bottom-level node and averaging its bit data up into a leaf node, pruning part of the tree.
[src:quadtree/octree] Once sampling is complete, exploring all routes in the tree down to the leaf nodes, taking note of the bits along the way, will yield approximately the required number of colors.
[src:quadtree/octree] The example recursive algorithm outline below (MATLAB syntax) decomposes an array of 3-dimensional points into octree style bins.
[src:quadtree/octree] The implementation begins with a single bin surrounding all given points, which then recursively subdivides into its 8 octree regions.
[src:quadtree/octree] Recursion is stopped when a given exit condition is met.
[src:quadtree/octree] Taking the full list of colors of a 24-bit RGB image as point input to the Octree point decomposition implementation outlined above, the following example show the results of octree color quantization.
[src:quadtree/octree] The first image is the original (532818 distinct colors), while the second is the quantized image (184 distinct colors) using octree decomposition, with each pixel assigned the color at the center of the octree bin in which it falls.
[src:quadtree/octree] Alternatively, final colors could be chosen at the centroid of all colors in each octree bin, however this added computation has very little effect on the visual result.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] A **quadtree** is a tree data structure in which each internal node has exactly four children.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Quadtrees are the two-dimensional analog of octrees and are most often used to partition a two-dimensional space by recursively subdividing it into four quadrants or regions.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] The data associated with a leaf cell varies by application, but the leaf cell represents a "unit of interesting spatial information".
[src:quadtree/quadtree] The subdivided regions may be square or rectangular, or may have arbitrary shapes.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Although similar subdivisions were used much earlier (for instance in the Whitney covering lemma of 1934), this data structure was named a quadtree by Raphael Finkel and J.L.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] A similar partitioning is also known as a *Q-tree*.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] A **tree-pyramid** (**T-pyramid**) is a "complete" tree; every node of the T-pyramid has four child nodes except leaf nodes; all leaves are on the same level, the level that corresponds to individual pixels in the image.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] The data in a tree-pyramid can be stored compactly in an array as an implicit data structure similar to the way a binary heap can store a complete binary tree compactly in an array.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Quadtrees may be classified according to the type of data they represent, including areas, points, lines and curves.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Quadtrees may also be classified by whether the shape of the tree is independent of the order in which data is processed.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] The following are common types of quadtrees.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] The region quadtree represents a partition of space in two dimensions by decomposing the region into four equal quadrants, subquadrants, and so on with each leaf node containing data corresponding to a specific subregion.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] It can be also interpreted as a method for "subpaving the region", based on set of hierarchical grids; or as a method of image compression, when an image is discretizated as a mosaic of "equal color regions".
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Each node in the tree either has exactly four children, or has no children (a leaf node).
[src:quadtree/quadtree] The height of quadtrees that follow this decomposition strategy (i.e. subdividing subquadrants as long as there is interesting data in the subquadrant for which more refinement is desired) is sensitive to and dependent on the spatial distribution of interesting areas in the space being decomposed.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] A region quadtree with a depth of n may be used to represent an image consisting of 2n × 2n pixels, where each pixel value is 0 or 1.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] The root node represents the entire image region.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] If the pixels in any region are not entirely 0s or 1s, it is subdivided.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] In this application, each leaf node represents a block of pixels that are all 0s or all 1s.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Note the potential savings in terms of space when these trees are used for storing images; images often have many regions of considerable size that have the same colour value throughout.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Rather than store a big 2-D array of every pixel in the image, a quadtree can capture the same information potentially many divisive levels higher than the pixel-resolution sized cells that we would otherwise require.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] The tree resolution and overall size is bounded by the pixel and image sizes.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] A region quadtree may also be used as a variable resolution representation of a data field.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] For example, the temperatures in an area may be stored as a quadtree, with each leaf node storing the average temperature over the subregion it represents.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] The point quadtree is an adaptation of a binary tree used to represent two-dimensional point data.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] It shares the features of all quadtrees but is a true tree as the center of a subdivision is always on a point.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] It is often very efficient in comparing two-dimensional, ordered data points, usually operating in O(log n) time.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Point quadtrees are worth mentioning for completeness, but they have been surpassed by *k*-d trees as tools for generalized binary search.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Point quadtrees with random insertion have been studied under the name **weighted planar stochastic lattices**.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Point quadtrees are constructed as follows.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Given the next point to insert, we find the cell in which it lies and add it to the tree.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] The new point is added such that the cell that contains it is divided into quadrants by the vertical and horizontal lines that run through the point.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Consequently, cells are rectangular but not necessarily square.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] In these trees, each node contains one of the input points.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Since the division of the plane is decided by the order of point-insertion, the tree's height is sensitive to and dependent on insertion order.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Inserting in a "bad" order can lead to a tree of height linear in the number of input points (at which point it becomes a linked-list).
[src:quadtree/quadtree] If the point-set is static, pre-processing can be done to create a tree of balanced height.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] A node of a point quadtree is similar to a node of a binary tree, with the major difference being that it has four pointers (one for each quadrant) instead of two ("left" and "right") as in an ordinary binary tree.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Also a key is usually decomposed into two parts, referring to x and y coordinates.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Point-region (PR) quadtrees are very similar to region quadtrees.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] The difference is the type of information stored about the cells.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] In a region quadtree, a uniform value is stored that applies to the entire area of the cell of a leaf.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] The cells of a PR quadtree, however, store a list of points that exist within the cell of a leaf.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] As mentioned previously, for trees following this decomposition strategy the height depends on the spatial distribution of the points.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Like the point quadtree, the PR quadtree may also have a linear height when given a "bad" set.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Edge quadtrees (much like PM quadtrees) are used to store lines rather than points.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Curves are approximated by subdividing cells to a very fine resolution, specifically until there is a single line segment per cell.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Near corners/vertices, edge quadtrees will continue dividing until they reach their maximum level of decomposition.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] This can result in extremely unbalanced trees which may defeat the purpose of indexing.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] The polygonal map quadtree (or PM Quadtree) is a variation of quadtree which is used to store collections of polygons that may be degenerate (meaning that they have isolated vertices or edges).
[src:quadtree/quadtree] A big difference between PM quadtrees and edge quadtrees is that the cell under consideration is not subdivided if the segments meet at a vertex in the cell.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] There are three main classes of PM Quadtrees, which vary depending on what information they store within each black node.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] PM3 quadtrees can store any amount of non-intersecting edges and at most one point.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] PM2 quadtrees are the same as PM3 quadtrees except that all edges must share the same end point.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Finally PM1 quadtrees are similar to PM2, but black nodes can contain a point and its edges or just a set of edges that share a point, but you cannot have a point and a set of edges that do not contain the point.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] This section summarizes a subsection from a book by Sariel Har-Peled.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] If we were to store every node corresponding to a subdivided cell, we may end up storing a lot of empty nodes.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] We can cut down on the size of such sparse trees by only storing subtrees whose leaves have interesting data (i.e.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] We can actually cut down on the size even further.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] When we only keep important subtrees, the pruning process may leave long paths in the tree where the intermediate nodes have degree two (a link to one parent and one child).
[src:quadtree/quadtree] It turns out that we only need to store the node u at the beginning of this path (and associate some meta-data with it to represent the removed nodes) and attach the subtree rooted at its end to u .
[src:quadtree/quadtree] It is still possible for these compressed trees to have a linear height when given "bad" input points.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Although we trim a lot of the tree when we perform this compression, it is still possible to achieve logarithmic-time search, insertion, and deletion by taking advantage of *Z*-order curves.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] The *Z*-order curve maps each cell of the full quadtree (and hence even the compressed quadtree) in $O(1)$ time to a one-dimensional line (and maps it back in $O(1)$ time too), creating a total order on the elements.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Therefore, we can store the quadtree in a data structure for ordered sets (in which we store the nodes of the tree).
[src:quadtree/quadtree] We must state a reasonable assumption before we continue: we assume that given two real numbers $\alpha ,\beta \in [0,1)$ expressed as binary, we can compute in $O(1)$ time the index of the first bit in which they differ.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] We also assume that we can compute in $O(1)$ time the lowest common ancestor of two points/cells in the quadtree and establish their relative *Z*-ordering, and we can compute the floor function in $O(1)$ time.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] With these assumptions, point location of a given point q (i.e. determining the cell that would contain q ), insertion, and deletion operations can all be performed in $O(\log {n})$ time (i.e. the time it takes to do a search in the underlying ordered set data structure).
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Else, find what would have been the lowest common ancestor of the point q and the cell v in an uncompressed quadtree.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Find the existing cell in the compressed tree that comes before u in the *Z*-order and return it.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Without going into specific details, to perform insertions and deletions we first do a point location for the thing we want to insert/delete, and then insert/delete it.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Care must be taken to reshape the tree as appropriate, creating and removing nodes as needed.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Quadtrees, particularly the region quadtree, have lent themselves well to image processing applications.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] We will limit our discussion to binary image data, though region quadtrees and the image processing operations performed on them are just as suitable for colour images.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] One of the advantages of using quadtrees for image manipulation is that the set operations of union and intersection can be done simply and quickly.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Given two binary images, the image union (also called *overlay*) produces an image wherein a pixel is black if either of the input images has a black pixel in the same location.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] That is, a pixel in the output image is white only when the corresponding pixel in *both* input images is white, otherwise the output pixel is black.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Rather than do the operation pixel by pixel, we can compute the union more efficiently by leveraging the quadtree's ability to represent multiple pixels with a single node.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] For the purposes of discussion below, if a subtree contains both black and white pixels we will say that the root of that subtree is coloured grey.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] The algorithm works by traversing the two input quadtrees ( $T_{1}$ and $T_{2}$ ) while building the output quadtree T .
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Informally, the algorithm is as follows.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Consider the nodes $v_{1}\in T_{1}$ and $v_{2}\in T_{2}$ corresponding to the same region in the images.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] While this algorithm works, it does not by itself guarantee a minimally sized quadtree.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] For example, consider the result if we were to union a checkerboard (where every tile is a pixel) of size $2^{k}\times 2^{k}$ with its complement.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] The result is a giant black square which should be represented by a quadtree with just the root node (coloured black), but instead the algorithm produces a full 4-ary tree of depth k .
[src:quadtree/quadtree] To fix this, we perform a bottom-up traversal of the resulting quadtree where we check if the four children nodes have the same colour, in which case we replace their parent with a leaf of the same colour.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] The intersection of two images is almost the same algorithm.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] One way to think about the intersection of the two images is that we are doing a union with respect to the *white* pixels.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] As such, to perform the intersection we swap the mentions of black and white in the union algorithm.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Consider two neighbouring black pixels in a binary image.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] They are *adjacent* if they share a bounding horizontal or vertical edge.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] In general, two black pixels are *connected* if one can be reached from the other by moving only to adjacent pixels (i.e. there is a path of black pixels between them where each consecutive pair is adjacent).
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Each maximal set of connected black pixels is a *connected component*.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Using the quadtree representation of images, Samet showed how we can find and label these connected components in time proportional to the size of the quadtree.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] This algorithm can also be used for polygon colouring.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] To simplify the discussion, let us assume the children of a node in the quadtree follow the *Z*-order (SW, NW, SE, NE).
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Since we can count on this structure, for any cell we know how to navigate the quadtree to find the adjacent cells in the different levels of the hierarchy.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Step one is accomplished with a post-order traversal of the quadtree.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] For each black leaf v we look at the node or nodes representing cells that are Northern neighbours and Eastern neighbours (i.e. the Northern and Eastern cells that share edges with the cell of v ).
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Since the tree is organized in *Z*-order, we have the invariant that the Southern and Western neighbours have already been taken care of and accounted for.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Let the Northern or Eastern neighbour currently under consideration be u .
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Step two can be accomplished using the union-find data structure.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] We start with each unique label as a separate set.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] For every equivalence relation noted in the first step, we union the corresponding sets.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Afterwards, each distinct remaining set will be associated with a distinct connected component in the image.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Step three performs another post-order traversal.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] This time, for each black node v we use the union-find's *find* operation (with the old label of v ) to find and assign v its new label (associated with the connected component of which v is part).
[src:quadtree/quadtree] This section summarizes a chapter from a book by Har-Peled and de Berg et al.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Mesh generation is essentially the triangulation of a point set for which further processing may be performed.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] As such, it is desirable for the resulting triangulation to have certain properties (like non-uniformity, triangles that are not "too skinny", large triangles in sparse areas and small triangles in dense ones, etc.) to make further processing quicker and less error-prone.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Quadtrees built on the point set can be used to create meshes with these desired properties.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Consider a leaf of the quadtree and its corresponding cell v .
[src:quadtree/quadtree] We say v is *balanced* (for mesh generation) if the cell's sides are intersected by the corner points of neighbouring cells at most once on each side.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] This means that the quadtree levels of leaves adjacent to v differ by at most one from the level of v .
[src:quadtree/quadtree] When this is true for all leaves, we say the whole quadtree is balanced (for mesh generation).
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Consider the cell v and the $5\times 5$ neighbourhood of same-sized cells centred at v .
[src:quadtree/quadtree] We call this neighbourhood the *extended cluster*.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] We say the quadtree is *well-balanced* if it is balanced, and for every leaf u that contains a point of the point set, its extended cluster is also in the quadtree and the extended cluster contains no other point of the point set.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] For every leaf, if there is a neighbour that is too large, subdivide the neighbour.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] This is repeated until the tree is balanced.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] We also make sure that for a leaf with a point in it, the nodes for each leaf's extended cluster are in the tree.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] For every leaf node v that contains a point, if the extended cluster contains another point, we further subdivide the tree and rebalance as necessary.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] If we needed to subdivide, for each child u of v we ensure the nodes of u 's extended cluster are in the tree (and re-balance as required).
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Repeat the previous step until the tree is well-balanced.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Transform the quadtree into a triangulation.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] We consider the corner points of the tree cells as vertices in our triangulation.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Before the transformation step we have a bunch of boxes with points in some of them.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] The remaining squares are triangulated according to some simple rules.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] For each regular square (no points within and no corner points in its sides), introduce the diagonal.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] Due to the way in which we separated points with the well-balancing property, no square with a corner intersecting a side is one that was warped.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] As such, we can triangulate squares with intersecting corners as follows.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] If there is one intersected side, the square becomes three triangles by adding the long diagonals connecting the intersection with opposite corners.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] If there are four intersected sides, we split the square in half by adding an edge between two of the four intersections, and then connect these two endpoints to the remaining two intersection points.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] For the other squares, we introduce a point in the middle and connect it to all four corners of the square as well as each intersection point.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] At the end of it all, we have a nice triangulated mesh of our point set built from a quadtree.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] The following pseudo code shows one means of implementing a quadtree which handles only points.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] It is assumed these structures are used.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] This class represents both one quad tree and the node where it is rooted.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] The following method inserts a point into the appropriate quad of a quadtree, splitting if necessary.
[src:quadtree/quadtree] The following method finds all points contained within a range.
[src:quadtree/space-partitioning] In geometry, **space partitioning** is the process of dividing an entire space (usually a Euclidean space) into two or more disjoint subsets (see also partition of a set).
[src:quadtree/space-partitioning] In other words, space partitioning divides a space into non-overlapping regions.
[src:quadtree/space-partitioning] Any point in the space can then be identified to lie in exactly one of the regions.
[src:quadtree/space-partitioning] Space-partitioning systems are often hierarchical, meaning that a space (or a region of space) is divided into several regions, and then the same space-partitioning system is recursively applied to each of the regions thus created.
[src:quadtree/space-partitioning] The regions can be organized into a tree, called a **space-partitioning tree**.
[src:quadtree/space-partitioning] Most space-partitioning systems use planes (or, in higher dimensions, hyperplanes) to divide space: points on one side of the plane form one region, and points on the other side form another.
[src:quadtree/space-partitioning] Points exactly on the plane are usually arbitrarily assigned to one or the other side.
[src:quadtree/space-partitioning] Recursively partitioning space using planes in this way produces a BSP tree, one of the most common forms of space partitioning.
[src:quadtree/space-partitioning] Space partitioning is particularly important in computer graphics, especially heavily used in ray tracing, where it is frequently used to organize the objects in a virtual scene.
[src:quadtree/space-partitioning] A typical scene may contain millions of polygons.
[src:quadtree/space-partitioning] Performing a ray/polygon intersection test with each would be a very computationally expensive task.
[src:quadtree/space-partitioning] Space partitioning is also often used in scanline algorithms to eliminate the polygons out of the camera's viewing frustum, limiting the number of polygons processed by the pipeline.
[src:quadtree/space-partitioning] There is also a usage in collision detection: determining whether two objects are close to each other can be much faster using space partitioning.
[src:quadtree/space-partitioning] In integrated circuit design, an important step is design rule check.
[src:quadtree/space-partitioning] This step ensures that the completed design is manufacturable.
[src:quadtree/space-partitioning] The check involves rules that specify widths and spacings and other geometry patterns.
[src:quadtree/space-partitioning] A modern design can have billions of polygons that represent wires and transistors.
[src:quadtree/space-partitioning] Efficient checking relies heavily on geometry query.
[src:quadtree/space-partitioning] For example, a rule may specify that any polygon must be at least *n* nanometers from any other polygon.
[src:quadtree/space-partitioning] This is converted into a geometry query by enlarging a polygon by *n/2* at all sides and query to find all intersecting polygons.
[src:quadtree/space-partitioning] The number of components in a space partition plays a central role in some results in probability theory.
[src:quadtree/space-partitioning] There are many studies and applications where Geographical Spatial Reality is partitioned by hydrological criteria, administrative criteria, mathematical criteria or many others.
[src:quadtree/space-partitioning] In the context of cartography and GIS - Geographic Information System, is common to identify cells of the partition by standard codes.
[src:quadtree/space-partitioning] For example the for HUC code identifying hydrographical basins and sub-basins, ISO 3166-2 codes identifying countries and its subdivisions, or arbitrary DGGs - discrete global grids identifying quadrants or locations.
[src:quadtree/space-partitioning] Suppose the n-dimensional Euclidean space is partitioned by r hyperplanes that are $(n-1)$ -dimensional.
[src:quadtree/space-partitioning] What is the number of components in the partition?
[src:quadtree/space-partitioning] The largest number of components is attained when the hyperplanes are in general position, i.e, no two are parallel and no three have the same intersection.
[src:quadtree/space-partitioning] Denote this maximum number of components by $Comp(n,r)$ .
[src:quadtree/space-partitioning] perpendicular hyperplanes; each additional hyperplane divides each existing component to 2).
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] Z-order curve iteration extended to three dimensions.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] It is named in France after Henri Lebesgue, who studied it in 1904, and named in the United States after Guy Macdonald Morton, who first applied the order to file sequencing in 1966.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] The z-value of a point in multidimensions is simply calculated by bit interleaving the binary representations of its coordinate values.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] However, when querying a multidimensional search range in these data, using binary search is not really efficient: It is necessary for calculating, from a point encountered in the data structure, the next possible Z-value which is in the multidimensional search range, called BIGMIN.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] The BIGMIN problem has first been stated and its solution shown by Tropf and Herzog in 1981.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] Once the data are sorted by bit interleaving, any one-dimensional data structure can be used, such as simple one dimensional arrays, binary search trees, B-trees, skip lists or (with low significant bits truncated) hash tables.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] The resulting ordering can equivalently be described as the order one would get from a depth-first traversal of a quadtree or octree.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] The figure below shows the Z-values for the two dimensional case with integer coordinates 0 ≤ *x* ≤ 7, 0 ≤ *y* ≤ 7 (shown both in decimal and binary).
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] Interleaving the binary coordinate values (starting to the right with the *x*-bit (in blue) and alternating to the left with the *y*-bit (in red)) yields the binary *z*-values (tilted by 45° as shown).
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] Connecting the *z*-values in their numerical order produces the recursively Z-shaped curve.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] Two-dimensional Z-values are also known as quadkey values.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] The Z-ordering can be used to efficiently build a quadtree (2D) or octree (3D) for a set of points.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] The basic idea is to sort the input set according to Z-order.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] Once sorted, the points can either be stored in a binary search tree and used directly, which is called a linear quadtree, or they can be used to build a pointer based quadtree.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] The input points are usually scaled in each dimension to be positive integers, either as a fixed point representation over the unit range [0, 1] or corresponding to the machine word size.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] Both representations are equivalent and allow for the highest order non-zero bit to be found in constant time.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] Each square in the quadtree has a side length which is a power of two, and corner coordinates which are multiples of the side length.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] Given any two points, the *derived square* for the two points is the smallest square covering both points.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] The interleaving of bits from the *x* and *y* components of each point is called the *shuffle* of *x* and *y*, and can be extended to higher dimensions.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] Points can be sorted according to their shuffle without explicitly interleaving the bits.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] To do this, for each dimension, the most significant bit of the exclusive or of the coordinates of the two points for that dimension is examined.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] The dimension for which the most significant bit is largest is then used to compare the two points to determine their shuffle order.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] The exclusive or operation masks off the higher order bits for which the two coordinates are identical.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] Since the shuffle interleaves bits from higher order to lower order, identifying the coordinate with the largest most significant bit, identifies the first bit in the shuffle order which differs, and that coordinate can be used to compare the two points.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] One way to determine whether the most significant bit is smaller is to compare the floor of the base-2 logarithm of each point.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] It is also possible to compare floating point numbers using the same technique.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] The `less_msb` function is modified to first compare the exponents.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] Only when they are equal is the standard `less_msb` function used on the mantissas.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] Once the points are in sorted order, two properties make it easy to build a quadtree: The first is that the points contained in a square of the quadtree form a contiguous interval in the sorted order.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] The second is that if more than one child of a square contains an input point, the square is the *derived square* for two adjacent points in the sorted order.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] For each adjacent pair of points, the derived square is computed and its side length determined.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] For each derived square, the interval containing it is bounded by the first larger square to the right and to the left in sorted order.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] Each such interval corresponds to a square in the quadtree.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] The result of this is a compressed quadtree, where only nodes containing input points or two or more children are present.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] A non-compressed quadtree can be built by restoring the missing nodes, if desired.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] Rather than building a pointer based quadtree, the points can be maintained in sorted order in a data structure such as a binary search tree.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] This allows points to be added and deleted in *O*(log *n*) time.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] Two quadtrees can be merged by merging the two sorted sets of points, and removing duplicates.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] Point location can be done by searching for the points preceding and following the query point in the sorted order.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] If the quadtree is compressed, the predecessor node found may be an arbitrary leaf inside the compressed node of interest.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] In this case, it is necessary to find the predecessor of the least common ancestor of the query point and the leaf found.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] By bit interleaving, the database records are converted to a (possibly very long) sequence of bits.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] The bit sequences are interpreted as binary numbers and the data are sorted or indexed by the binary values, using any one dimensional data structure, as mentioned in the introduction.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] However, when querying a multidimensional search range in these data, using binary search is not really efficient.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] In this example, the range being queried (*x* = 2, ..., 3, *y* = 2, ..., 6) is indicated by the dotted rectangle.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] In this example, the value *F* = 19 is encountered when searching a data structure in increasing Z-value direction, so we would have to search in the interval between *F* and MAX (hatched area).
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] To speed up the search, one would calculate the next Z-value which is in the search range, called BIGMIN (36 in the example) and only search in the interval between BIGMIN and MAX (bold values), thus skipping most of the hatched area.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] Searching in decreasing direction is analogous with LITMAX which is the highest Z-value in the query range lower than *F*.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] The BIGMIN problem has first been stated and its solution shown in Tropf and Herzog.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] For the history after the publication see.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] With a general record comparison function (greater-less-equal, in the sense of z-value), complications with bit sequences length exceeding the computer word length are avoided, and the code can easily be adapted to any number of dimensions and any record key word length.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] As the approach does not depend on the one dimensional data structure chosen, there is still free choice of structuring the data, so well known methods such as balanced trees can be used to cope with dynamic data, and keeping the tree balance when inserting or deleting takes O(log n) time.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] The method is also used in UB-trees (balanced).
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] The Free choice makes it easier to incorporate the method into existing databases.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] This is in contrast for example to R-trees where special considerations are necessary.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] Z-order is one of the few multidimensional access methods that has found its way into commercial database systems.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] The method is used in various technical applications of different fields. and in commercial database systems.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] As long ago as 1966, G.M.Morton proposed Z-order for file sequencing of a static two dimensional geographical database.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] Areal data units are contained in one or a few quadratic frames represented by their sizes and lower right corner Z-values, the sizes complying with the Z-order hierarchy at the corner position.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] With high probability, changing to an adjacent frame is done with one or a few relatively small scanning steps.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] As an alternative, the Hilbert curve has been suggested as it has a better order-preserving behaviour, and, in fact, was used in an optimized index, the S2-geometry.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] Effective use of Strassen multiplication with Z-order has been demonstrated, see Valsalam and Skjellum's 2002 paper.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] Buluç *et al.* present a sparse matrix data structure that Z-orders its non-zero elements to enable parallel matrix-vector multiplication.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] Matrices in linear algebra can also be traversed using a space-filling curve.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] Conventional loops traverse a matrix row by row.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] Traversing with the Z-curve allows efficient access to the memory hierarchy.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] Some GPUs store texture maps in Z-order to increase spatial locality of reference during texture mapped rasterization.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] This allows cache lines to represent rectangular tiles, increasing the probability that nearby accesses are in the cache.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] At a larger scale, it also decreases the probability of costly, so called, "page breaks" (i.e., the cost of changing rows) in SDRAM/DDRAM.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] This is important because 3D rendering involves arbitrary transformations (rotations, scaling, perspective, and distortion by animated surfaces).
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] These formats are often referred to as *swizzled textures* or *twiddled textures*.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] The Barnes–Hut algorithm requires construction of an octree.
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] Storing the data as a pointer-based tree requires many sequential pointer dereferences to iterate over the octree in depth-first order (expensive on a distributed-memory machine).
[src:quadtree/z-order-curve] Instead, if one stores the data in a hashtable, using octree hashing, the Z-order curve naturally iterates the octree in depth-first order.
